"policy_citations":[
{
"source":"aml_thresholds.md",
"text":"## Typologies to detect\n- **Structuring / smurfing:** multiple deposits kept **just under INR 50,000** to avoid\n  reporting, often across several accounts that funnel to one beneficiary within days.\n- **Layering (circular transfers):** funds moved through a chain of accounts (A\u2192B\u2192C\u2192A)\n  to obscure origin, with little economic substance.\n- **Shared-device / linked-identity rings:** multiple ostensibly unrelated accounts\n  transacting from the **same device or IP** in a short window.",
"score":0.11
},
{
"source":"procurement_policy.md",
"text":"# Procurement Policy & Thresholds (sample \u2014 synthetic, vertical #2)\n\n> Illustrative only. Demonstrates the Sovereign AIP engine reused for a second\n> workflow: same ontology + action + governance pattern, new domain.",
"score":0.046
},
{
"source":"procurement_policy.md",
"text":"## Recommended dispositions\n- **APPROVE** \u2014 within budget, known vendor, documented need.\n- **ESCALATE** \u2014 over budget or high-risk vendor; route to the controller.\n- **REJECT** \u2014 no budget, sanctioned vendor, or no legitimate business purpose.",
"score":0.034
}
],
"str_narrative":"A suspicious transaction pattern has been identified corresponding to the typology of structuring/smurfing. This activity involves 6 mule accounts (ACC-MULE-01 through ACC-MULE-06) receiving multiple sub-INR50,000 deposits via 2 transactions (TXN-R00011 and TXN-R00023), suggesting an attempt to avoid reporting requirements by fragmenting large sums into smaller transactions. The funds were subsequently funnelled onward in larger lumps, also in contravention of the matched policy clause. Each of these mule accounts transacted within a short window from the same IP device as a separate account. The activity lacks apparent lawful purpose and appears structured to evade detection rules. This pattern is consistent with the behaviour described under structuring/smurfing.",
"source":"cached"
},
